 class="display_none" id="a_Hospitality">\r\n        <h3>Hospitality &amp;Tourism:</h3>\r\n        <p>India’s growing appetite for High end coffee bars, fast foods chains for pizzas, burgers and French fries are set to swell the size of the country’s fast-food market to double its current size by 2016.</p>\r\n        <p>According to a report published by Crisil, the Indian unit of Standard & Poor’s rating agency, the fast -food segment will be worth Rs.7000 crores ($1.1 billion) in three years. In India over the next three years, new store additions by fast-food companies selling Western-style food will increase by 16%-18% annually — nearly half of those will be in smaller cities.</p>\r\n        <h3>Hospitality Course Contents:</h3>\r\n        <ol>\r\n            <li>INTRODUCTION</li>\r\n            <li>SERVER FUNCTION AND RESPONSIBILITIES</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>General Job Guidelines and Responsibilities</li>\r\n                <li>Server Opening Procedures</li>\r\n                <li>Server Closing Procedures</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>THE GUEST</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Service</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>QUALITY CONTROL</li>\r\n            <li>TABLE INTRODUCTION</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Ordering Procedures</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>PERSONAL APPEARANCE</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Uniform</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>SUGGESTIVE SELLING</li>\r\n            <li>SPECIALS &FEATURES OF THE DAY</li>\r\n            <li>COFFEE-TEA DESSERTS</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Coffee & Tea</li>\r\n                <li>Desserts</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>CLOSING OUT A TABLE</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Presenting the Check</li>\r\n                <li>The Farewell</li>\r\n                <li>Methods of Payment</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>CHECK-OUT PROCEDURES</li>\r\n            <ul>\r\n                <li>Over Rings or Voids</li>\r\n                <li>House Promo</li>\r\n                <li>Manager Promo</li>\r\n                <li>Employee Discount/Customer Discount</li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <li>SANITATION</li>\r\n            <li>SAFETY</li>\r\n            <li>CONCLUSION</li>\r\n        </ol>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- Banking-->\r\n<div class="display_none" id="a_Banking">\r\n\r\n        <h3>Banking & Finance:</h3>\r\n        <p>Today, the banking sector in India is fairly mature interms of supply, product range and reach. With passing time, Indian economy is further expected to grow and be strong for quite some time-especially in its services sector. The demand for banking services, especially retail banking, mortgages and investment services are expected to grow stronger. The significant change in the policy and attitude that currently being seen is encouraging for the bajing sector growth.</p>\r\n        <p>Currently, India has 88 scheduled commercial banks, 28 public sector banks, 29 private banks and 31 foreign banks. The compbined network of branches are over 60,000 with around 20,000 ATMs.</p>\r\n        <p>According to ICRA Ltd, 75% of total assets of the banking industry in India belong to Public sector banks. Despite slow down in world econmy Banking Industry in India will positively grow in the coming years.</p>\r\n        <p>With more and more services like credit cards, consumer loans, home loans etc., will keep growing in the market where 65% of the population is less than the age of 35 which definitely ensures a positive growth in the services mentioned above. To augment such growth, what it needs is a well-trained youth to join the banking industry and involve in the process of delivering all services that banking industry provide.</p>\r\n        <p>To know the course content of Banking and Financial Services click here:</p>\r\n        <h3>Banking & Finance Course Content:</h3>\r\n        <ol>\r\n        <li>Banking Basics: Principles of Banking and its structures- Retail Banking- E Banking-KYC.</li>\r\n        <li>Functions of Banks: Deposits-Banker Customer Relations-KYC Guidelines-Services by Banks</li>\r\n        <li>Marketing of Banking Services Products: Marketing of Services-Role of DSA/DMA in Bank Markting, Channel Management-Selling Function-Tele Marketing/Mobile phone Banking.</li>\r\n        <li>Indian Financial System: Market Structure-SEBI, RBI,IRDA functions- Regulatory provisions Retail, Whole sale Banking-Fair prices for debt collections.</li>\r\n        <li>Summary of Various Products: Credit Cards-Consumer, Vehicle, Home loans etc.,-Agri Credit Products.</li>\r\n        <li>Recovery Procedures: Recovery agents-Procedures of Recovery-NPA-Legal Aspects in recovery-Bank Procedures and Debt Collection Skills – Case Studies.</li>\r\n        </ol>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- Retail-->\r\n<div class="display_none" id="a_Retail">\r\n\r\n        <h3>Retail Management:</h3>\r\n        <p>Retailing in India is one of the pillars of its economy and accounts for 14 to 15 percent of its GDP. The Indian retail market is estimated to be US$ 450 billion and one of the top five retail markets in the world by economic value. India is one of the fastest growing retail markets in the world, with 1.2 billion people.</p>\r\n        <p>As of 2013, India''s retailing industry was essentially owner manned small shops. In 2010, larger format convenience stores and supermarkets accounted for about 4 percent of the industry, and these were present only in large urban centers. India''s retail and logistics industry employs about 40 million Indians (3.3% of Indian population)</p>\r\n        <p>Total retail employment in India, both organized and unorganized, account for about 6% of Indian labour work force currently - most of which is unorganized. This is about a third of levels in United States and Europe; and about half of levels in other emerging economies. A complete expansion of retail sector to levels and productivity similar to other emerging economies and developed economies such as the United States would create over 50 million jobs in India. </p>\r\n        <p>Hence, Training and Development of labour and management for higher retail productivity is expected to be a challenge.</p>\r\n        <p>KVM Academy is eminently positioned to carryout skill development program specific to Retail Industry with focus on Customer Relationship Management at all levels. The Course content would include broadly Retail sales management, Elements of Materials management and Human Resource Management. Along with these, soft skills like communications, behavioral aspects, etiquette, dress code, etc., would also be developed.</p>\r\n        <h3>Retailing Course Contents:</h3>\r\n        <p>The Retail Industry and its Environment: Introduction to Retailing—Retail Organization and Formats Retailing and the Competitive Environment Customers Formulating and Implementing Retail Strategy: Formulating Retail Strategy Implementing Retail Strategy—Retail Logistics Information Technology and Retailing Retail Marketing Management: Retail Location Retail Design and Visual Merchandising¬ Retail Buying Retail Brands Retail Pricing—Retail Promotion—Retail Services. Retail Challaenges: International Retailing Internet Retailing—Legal and Ethical Issues in Retailing</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- Insurance-->\r\n<div class="display_none" id="a_Insurance">\r\n        <h3>Insurance:</h3>\r\n        <p>With the opening up of the insurance sector in 2000, many leading foreign players entered India in both life & non life insurance. As per the current regulations FDI in insurance sector is limited to 26% . So most foreign players tied up with Indian companies and started business. There is a strong demand to increase the FDI to 46%, but it is pending decision of the parliament for many years.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>The leading companies in life insurance other than the state owned LIC are SBI Life Insurance Company limited, ICICI Prudential Life Insurance Company limited, HDFC Life, Bajaj Allianz Life Insurance Company limited and Max Life. There are 24 Life insurance companies operating in India now. The life insurance segment contributes about 4.4 per cent to India’s gross domestic product (GDP) in terms of total premiums underwritten annually. This is too low compared to the global average. Since the life insurance sector was opened up in 2000, it has now gone through two clear cycles - the first of very high growth (CAGR of over 12 per cent in number of new policies between 2000-10) and then one of substantive moderation (CAGR of over 9 per cent between 2010-13). Despite this, long-term growth prospects for the industry remain intact. \r\n        With huge educated young population entering the working class in the coming years, the future of life insurance in India is very bright in the coming days.  It is estimated that the sector will grow at a compounded average growth rate of 15-20 per cent over the next 15-20 years.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>The public sector companies in non life insurance sector are New India , National, Oriental and United India. ICICI Lombard ,Bajaj Allianz, HDFC Ergo, Iffco – Tokio and Reliance General are the leading players in the private sector. Totally there are 28 non life insurance companies operating in India.  The non life premium was growing at 11% for the period 2000- 2013. Notwithstanding the rapid growth of the sector over the last decade, insurance in India remains at an early stage of development. The Indian insurance market (in terms of premium volume) was the 19th largest in the world. This was despite India being the second most populous country in the world as well as a leading economy. This shows the scope for the growth in the non life insurance sector in India.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Our country of a billion plus population is going to be the next growth engine for the world economy and insurance industry can play a huge role in the long term financing of the country’s economy. This offers tremendous opportunities both directly and indirectly to the educated youth of the country. While there will be huge opportunities in sales and distribution, there will be good number of opportunities in policy servicing, claim processing, actuarial services, underwriting, investments etc. There will be demand for trained people in these specialized areas when the industry is poised for the next high growth phase.</p>\r\n\r\n        <h3>Insurance Course Content:</h3>\r\n        <p>Origin of Insurance and its Elementary Aspects: Concepts, Modern forms, Regulation, Milestones and Basics Principles of Insurance.</p>\r\n        <p>Principles of Life Insurance: Introduction—Characteristics of Life Insurance Contract, Essentials of Valid Contracts—Difference between Life Insurance and Other Insurance.</p>\r\n        <p>Life Insurance Products: Introduction—Financial Needs, Term Life, Endowment Assurance Policies, Whole Life, UnitLinked, and Annuity Policies, Group Insurance, Riders etc.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Policy Conditions: Introduction—Policy Provisions, Structure, Conditions and Privileges-Typical Policy Bond Structure, Supplementary Benefits and Unit Linked Policy''s special Provisions.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Life Insurance Underwriting: Risk Classifications, Purposes and Methods, Factors affecting Mortality, Assessment of Risk, Incidence and Method of Extra Risk taking, Underwriting Process.</p>\r\n          \r\n        <p>Pricing: Basic Elements in Computation and Mortality, Premium Calculation, Level and Net Premium Calculation, Office Premium, Policy Valuation and its Methods.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Policy Servicing: Importance and Nature of Policy Servicing, Organization Structure and Departmentalization of Insurance Companies.</p>\r\n\r\n        <p>Policy Benefits Payment: Guidlines, Classification etc.,--Surrender Benefits, Maturity, Death and Repudiation of Claims, Evidence of Titile, Nomination, Assignment, Intestate Claims, Payments of Annuities and Claims on Small Life Insurance Policies.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<!-- JS Menu -->\r\n<script type="text/javascript" src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-1.10.2.min.js"></script><script type="text/javascript">// <![CDATA[\r\n$(document).ready(function(){ 	$(''.toggle_services'').click(function(){ 		var id=$(this).attr(''id''); 		$(''.display_none'').removeClass(''display_block''); 		$(''#a_''+id).addClass(''display_block''); 		$(''.toggle_services'').removeClass(''active''); 		$(this).addClass(''active''); 	}); });\r\n// ]]></script>', 'Course Details', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'open', '', '143-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-13 07:41:02', '2014-02-13 07:41:02', '', 143, 'http://kvmacademy.com/143-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
